ce:section.ce:para:
The chronoamperometry technique has been utilized for the trace-level electrochemical detection of mercury at a constant applied potential of 0.18 V with the 5CD@Ce-BTC modified GCE in 0.1 M PBS electrolyte (pH-7), and the results are shown in (Fig. 2
                           a&b). As we can see there is a linear increase in the current response for every concentration of mercury. The current response was linear for the subsequent addition of mercury and the wide linear range was found to be 0.001 µM–10 µM (Fig. 2b). There are two linear ranges present from 0.001 µM–0.01 µM and 0.5 µM–10 µM with a correlation coefficient of 0.9901 and 0.9761 respectively. The low limit of detection was found to be 0.5 nM (inset of Fig. 2b), which is convincingly lesser than the threshold value set by the World Health Organization for mercury (30 nM), with ultra-high sensitivity of 32.66 µA nM−1 cm−2. These results have confirmed the prepared 5CD@Ce-BTC modified GCE was stable and its anti-fouling property enhances its sensitivity for repeated measurements. The comparison table of this work with previously reported materials for the sensing of mercury is given in (Table 1
                           ).

Chronoamperometry studies of the 5CD@Ce-BTC modified GCE for the trace-level electrochemical detection of tetracycline at a constant applied potential of 0.84 V, are shown in the figure (Fig. 4
                           a). As we can see there is a linear increase in the current response for every concentration of tetracycline. The current response was linear for the subsequent addition of tetracycline and the wide linear range was found to be 0.1–90 µM. There are two linear ranges present from 0.1–1 µM to 3 µM–90 µM with a correlation coefficient of 0.9921 and 0.9856 respectively. The low limit of detection was calculated to be 30 nM (inset of Fig. 4b) with a high sensitivity of 7.52 µA nM−1 cm−2. These results have confirmed the prepared 5CD@Ce-BTC modified GCE was stable and its anti-fouling property enhances its sensitivity for repeated measurements. The comparison table of this work with previously reported materials for the sensing of tetracycline is given in (Table 2
                           ).

The real sample analysis was done to evaluate the practicability of the reported sensor in detecting mercury and tetracycline. For this study, the 5CD@Ce-BTC modified GCE was investigated with the environmental samples (Groundwater and Lake water). The 0.1 M PBS was used to keep the medium pH constant and the collected water samples were used without prior treatment. The results of the real sample analysis of mercury and tetracycline are displayed in (Tables 3
                         and 4
                        ) respectively, and these findings show that the 5CD@Ce-BTC modified GCE sensor could be used for the sensitive detection of these analytes in the environmental samples.
